ce:section.ce:para:
As a result of conducting a qualitative test for Campylobacter in chicken carcasses using conventional method, Campylobacter was not detected in any of the chicken carcasses (Table 2
                        ). For the samples enriched with CEB and NCEB-5 in the MDS, all 10 chicken samples were negative for Campylobacter (Table 2). Hence, it was assumed that Campylobacter did not contaminate the chicken carcasses. According to Wei et al. (2016), Campylobacter was more easily detected in duck carcasses than in chicken carcasses (Wei et al., 2016). Thus, duck samples were purchased and analyzed using the conventional method and the MDS. Campylobacter was detected in 3 out of 30 samples using the conventional method (Table 2, Fig. 2
                        ). However, the results obtained with the MDS after enrichment in CEB and NCEB-5 showed that Campylobacter was detected in all 30 samples (Table 2). Thus, it was confirmed that the use of the MDS improved the detection efficiency. In a previous study, the LAMP assay and PCR methods were compared to confirm their ability of detection of C. jejuni from cattle farm samples (Dong et al., 2014). The detection ability of the LAMP assay was found to be better than that of the PCR method because the LAMP assay was less sensitive to potential inhibitors, such as protein or fat, and its detection limit was low. Campylobacter is present in many environmental samples, and because even less than 500 Campylobacter cells can cause infection in humans (He et al., 2013), a LAMP assay with a low detection limit is effective. The MDS also utilizes the LAMP principle and thus can show better detection efficiency than the conventional method involving PCR.

When comparing the detection efficiency of the MDS after enrichment in CEB and NCEB-5 at the different time points, Campylobacter detection was positive at 9 h for both CEB and NCEB-5. In addition, in duck samples 11 and 13, Campylobacter detection was positive at 6 h when enriched in NCEB-5 (Table 3
                        ). Thus, it could be confirmed that NCEB-5 had better enrichment ability than CEB. In 6 out of 10 duck samples, Campylobacter was detected in NCEB-5 within 5 h but not in CEB (Table 4
                        ). This indicates that N-CNDs added to CEB accelerated the growth of Campylobacter.
